g.text: RetroPath2.0
The RetroPath2.0 workflow build a reaction network from a set of source compounds to a set of sink compounds.
When applied in a retrosynthetic fashion, the source is composed of the target compounds and the sink is composed of the available
reactants (for instance in the context of metabolic engineering the sink is the set of native metabolites of a chassis strain). From
amongst all the chemical reactions generated using RetroPath2.0 (in the retrosynthetic way), only a subset may effectively link a source
to a subset of sink compounds. This sub-network is considered as a scope and is output in dedicated files (see below).
The workflow handles both monomolecular (1 substrate) and bimolecular (2 substrates) reactions.
Getting started
1. Double click on the
Input configuration
node and set appropriate values. Please refer to the embedded help panel for specification
on input files and parameters ("question mark" button at the bottom of the Input configuration panel).
2. Double click on the
Output configuration
node and set appropriate values. Please refer to the embedded help panel for dedicated
information. ("question mark" button at the bottom of the Output configuration panel).
3. Right click on the
Core
node and select "Execute". A green dot will appear under the Core node on successful execution.
4. In order to investigate any scope found, please use the "scope.html" file: open it with a web browser and follow the instructions
displayed (Firefox or Google Chrome recommended).
Usage specifications
- RetroPath2.0 current release is compatible starting from version 3.3.6 of Knime Analytics Platform. Check older RetroPath2.0 release
for using it with older version of KNIME.
Limitations as of 2018/07/30
- Scope is only relevant for retrosynthetic usage (target/source to chassis/sink).

Dev/Advanced user features:
The features below are activable through the global workflow variables pane.
#== Use the "Fire" Python Snippet for firing rules
A python snippet is embedded into the workflow allowing an enhanced way of firing rules. The "Fire" python snippet allows one to
compute bigger metabolic maps thanks to a drastically improved memory management. This feature can be enabled at the cost of some
python dependancies (see below) and is available for Linux systems.
Set the "dev.use-py-fire" global workflow variable to 1 in order to enable the feature. Timeout and multihreading settings are adjustable
using the "dev.py-fire-timeout" and "dev.py-fire-procs", respectively.
Setting up the python environment assuming you are using conda for managing python environments (https://www.continuum.io):
1) Create the environment and install packages:
conda create --name pyknime python=2.7
source activate pyknime
conda install --channel rdkit rdkit # Please use rdkit release 2016.03.1 or later
conda install pandas protobuf psutil
2) Get the python path
source activate test
which python
3) Set this python path into Knime settings
For more details: https://www.knime.org/blog/how-to-setup-the-python-extension
4) Restart Knime
#== Disable Scope filters
The scope computation involves several heuristic filters in order to remove undesirable reactions. Such highly undesirable reactions are
those promoting metabolic loops increasing the connectivity of metabolic graphs.
One can disable these filters using the (i) "dev.scope-filter-stepback", (ii)"dev.scope-filter-samestep" and (iii) "dev.scope-filter-bootstrap"
global workflow variables. Variables noted (i) and (ii) control respectively the removing of reactions producing a "not in sink" compound
that has been already produced at (i) a previous iteration of the metabolic graph traversal and at (ii) the same iteration than the substrate,
while (iii) controls the filtering of reactions that involve compounds simultaneously present in both left and right hand sides.
#== Change the chunk size of the source loop (outer loop)
By design, the source loop (outer loop) of the workflow is set so that source compounds provided by the user are treated one by one. This
is the recommended setting for a retrosynthetic usage as it ensures the best metabolic space exploration.
One can change this value using the "dev.source-chunk-size" global workflow variable.
#== Disable parsing of the left hand side of SMARTS rules (prefiltering task)
The workflow performs an optimization procedure before firing the rules using a prefiltering task. During this task, the workflow detects
and removes surrouding brakets on the left hand side of the rules.
One can disable this behavour using the "dev.prefilter-rm-brakets" global workflow variable.
However, we strongly recommend to not change the value unless you (really) know what you are doing.
Double-click top left corner to edit.
